Project: Investigate Medical no-show appointments dataset¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

This dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row.

Questions that we will answer:

  • Does receiving an SMS encourage the patient go to the appointment?
  • Does gender affect the attendance rate?
  • Does Age affect the attendance rate?
  • Does Neighbourhood affect the attendance rate?
  • How does variables correlate to each other

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Now that we've trimmed and cleaned the data, we're ready to move on to exploration. using visualizations to answer questions

# Histograms of all columns in the dataset

Does receiving an SMS encourage the patient go to the appointment?¶

In [14]:
df['SMS_received'].value_counts()
Out[14]:
0    75044
1    35482
Name: SMS_received, dtype: int64

The number of patients who received an SMS are nearly half the number of patients who didn't receive an SMS

In [15]:
# we make two datasets, one that contains patients who received SMS and the other one contains patients who didn't receive an SMS 
sms = df.query('SMS_received == 1')
no_sms = df.query('SMS_received == 0')
In [16]:
# making pie charts to draw conclusions
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(5,5), dpi=200)
ax1 = fig.add_subplot(121)
sms['No_show'].value_counts().plot(kind='pie',ax=ax1,autopct='%1.1f%%',startangle=270, fontsize=6,labels= None,subplots=True)
plt.title('Patients who received SMS',fontsize=7)
plt.ylabel('')
plt.legend(loc=4,prop={'size': 3.5},labels=["showed","didn't show"])
ax2 = fig.add_subplot(122)
no_sms['No_show'].value_counts().plot(kind='pie',ax=ax2,autopct='%1.1f%%',startangle=270, fontsize=6,labels= None,subplots=True)
plt.title("Patients who didn't received SMS",fontsize=7)
plt.ylabel('')
plt.legend(loc=4,prop={'size': 3.5},labels=["showed","didn't show"])
plt.show()

We conclude that 83.3% of the patients who didn't receive an SMS showed for their appointment, while only 72.4% of the patients who received an SMS showed for their appointment. That is quite odd as one might think that receiving an SMS will encourage the patient to commit to their appointment.

Does gender affect the attendance rate?¶

In [17]:
# Create two datasets to identify who showed for their appointment and who didn't
show = df.query('No_show=="No"')
noshow = df.query('No_show=="Yes"')
In [18]:
# create functions that return specific coulmns from show and noshow datasets
def showed(variable):
    return show[variable]
def no_show(variable):
    return noshow[variable]
In [19]:
show['Gender'].value_counts()
Out[19]:
F    57245
M    30962
Name: Gender, dtype: int64
In [20]:
noshow['Gender'].value_counts()
Out[20]:
F    14594
M     7725
Name: Gender, dtype: int64
In [21]:
# making pie charts to visualize the gender of people who showed and people who didn't show
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(5,5), dpi=200)
ax1 = fig.add_subplot(121)
showed('Gender').value_counts().plot(kind='pie',ax=ax1,autopct='%1.1f%%',startangle=270, fontsize=6,labels= None,subplots=True)
plt.title('patients who showed',fontsize=7)
plt.ylabel('')
plt.legend(loc=4,prop={'size': 3.5},labels=["Female","Male"])
ax2 = fig.add_subplot(122)
no_show('Gender').value_counts().plot(kind='pie',ax=ax2,autopct='%1.1f%%',startangle=270, fontsize=6,labels= None,subplots=True)
plt.title("patients who didn't show",fontsize=7)
plt.ylabel('')
plt.legend(loc=4,prop={'size': 3.5},labels=["Female","Male"])
plt.show()

We see that the decision of the patient to show or not isn't affected much by the patients gender, as the percentages of males and females who showed or didn't show are quite similar.

Does Age affect the attendance rate?¶

In [22]:
# visualize the attendance rates of different age groups 
plt.figure(figsize=(16,8.5))
showed('Age').plot(kind='hist',alpha=.5,color='blue',label='showed')
no_show('Age').plot(kind='hist',alpha=.5,color='red',label="didn't show")
plt.legend()
plt.title("comparison of different age groups",fontsize=20)
plt.xlabel('age')
plt.ylabel('number of patients')
plt.grid()
plt.show()

The histogram shows that patients who are under 10 have the highest attendance rate, and the patients who are over 60 have lower attendance rate.

Does Neighbourhood affect the attendance rate?¶

In [23]:
# compare patients based on their neighbourhood
plt.figure(figsize=(16,8.5))
showed('Neighbourhood').value_counts().plot(kind='bar',alpha=1,color='blue',label='show')
no_show('Neighbourhood').value_counts().plot(kind='bar',alpha=1,color='red',label='noshow')
plt.legend()
plt.title('comparison based on neighbourhood',fontsize=20)
plt.ylabel('number of patients')
plt.xlabel('neighbourhood')
plt.show()

we can see from the graph that the number of patients showing for the appointment are strongly affected by the neighbourhood and the number of patients from this neighbourhood.

Conclusions¶
In conclusion, the number of patients are affected by the neighbourhood and also the SMS received by the patient. surprisingly,
the patients who didn't receive an SMS have a higher rate of attendance. Also, we conclude that age affect the attendance rate
as patients under 60 have a high rate of attendance compared to patients over 60. we also concluded that gender doesn't really affect the attendance rate that much as males and females have a relatively similar attendance rates. Finally we saw the different correlations between the variables and we concluded that relationships between age/hypertension, age/diabetes, hypertension/diabetes are positively correlated.


Limitations¶
The data are collected unevenly between different neighbourhoods, some neighbourhoods have a lot bigger numbers of patients than other neigbourhoods. Also, alot of patients age values are 0.
